<span id="freeTextContainer9746178305561008087">I&apos;m being very generous when I give this 2 stars. I&apos;m going to give it the benefit of the doubt that, because it&apos;s a &apos;translation&apos;, something is lost between the original and the translated version. Actually a lot is lost, but that may be neither here nor there. I still think that despite the loss of the subtlety of languages, one still has to have an ability to write in the first place. Mathias Malzieu doesn&apos;t have that. A singer he may be. Creative he may be. But a writer he is not. Least ways</span>
  <span id="freeText9746178305561008087" style="display:none">I'm being very generous when I give this 2 stars. I'm going to give it the benefit of the doubt that, because it's a 'translation', something is lost between the original and the translated version. Actually a lot is lost, but that may be neither here nor there. I still think that despite the loss of the subtlety of languages, one still has to have an ability to write in the first place. Mathias Malzieu doesn't have that. A singer he may be. Creative he may be. But a writer he is not. Least ways, not beyond lyrics.<br /><br />To sum it up - this book is totally Emo. Badly written Emo. Lots of angst and a million metaphors to paint a portrait of heart felt love and emotions. <br /><br />Blechhh.<br /><br />I'll fess up that I was completely sucked into the front cover. I have a artistic weakness for that kind of drawing. It lures me like a bee to honey. I am one of those readers that often will pick up a book because of that lure.. *sigh*. <br /><br />The biggest positive this book has - beyond the front cover - is that it is blessedly short.</span>
