<span id="freeTextContainer9564881461814142685">That was...well crap.<br/><br/>Jack&apos;s heart is a cuckoo-clock and so weak that his foster mom tells him he must never fall in love or he&apos;ll die when his heart gets broken. Of course, he still falls in love after meeting a girl, talking to her, slowly getting to know her...no wait sorry. He sees her, doesn&apos;t exchange one personal word with her but she&apos;s hot and that&apos;s twu luv rite? Anyway, he&apos;s so smitten that he decides to follow her to Spain (Jack&apos;s from Edinburgh). On the way there he picks up a depress</span>
  <span id="freeText9564881461814142685" style="display:none">That was...well crap.<br /><br />Jack's heart is a cuckoo-clock and so weak that his foster mom tells him he must never fall in love or he'll die when his heart gets broken. Of course, he still falls in love after meeting a girl, talking to her, slowly getting to know her...no wait sorry. He sees her, doesn't exchange one personal word with her but she's hot and that's twu luv rite? Anyway, he's so smitten that he decides to follow her to Spain (Jack's from Edinburgh). On the way there he picks up a depressed French magician who's not so depressed that he can't have random threesomes so the book can refer to "giggling breasts and butts accompanying him" Women with personality or agency? Not in this book.<br /><br />Jack even finds his <i>one true love</i> but fucks everything up. Because who should he rather believe? The woman he loves and who has assured him that she loves him or a dude he knows hates him from the bottom of his heart? Well obviously only men can be trusted and that whore must be lying. (Did I mention that Jack #NotAllMens her at one point? No Jack, not all men but <i>definitely</i> you).<br /><br />Besides: things that are mentioned in this book that is set between the years 1874 and mid-1890s:<br />- the football world cup<br />- musicals<br />- infusions<br />- intergalactic space journalism</span>
